    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "a571209a51dd3ce2",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "a571209a51dd3ce2",
        "text": "We still have to work a bit on this concept of structural coupling, especially in the respect that a coupling, as the concept of form suggests to us, is a two-sided form. It does not refer to the entire environment, because not everything that exists at all is structurally coupled to the system. Rather, the couplings are highly selective. Something is included, and something else is excluded. The excluded may well affect the system causally, but then only destructively. In the area of structural coupling, on the other hand, possibilities are stored which the system can use, which it can transform into information. From this point of view, one could say that structural coupling has on the one hand an exclusion effect - in this domain the system is indifferent - and on the other hand causes a channeling of causalities which the system can use. This preserves the feature of the concept that structural coupling is always compatible with autopoiesis; ibid. there are ways to influence the system insofar as autopoiesis is not destroyed. One can perhaps reformulate this by saying that the splitting of the environment by structural coupling into excluded and included tends to reduce and tailor the relevant relations between environment and system to a narrow range of influence, and that only then can a system do something with irritations and causalities. Only if not everything affects the system simultaneously, but highly selective patterns are available, the system can react to irritations and \"perturbations\" (Maturana), i.e. understand them as information and adapt the structures accordingly or use operations accordingly to transform the structures."
