      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "195800424ca5a6df",
        "text": "Because there is no cultural program for individuality. There is, of course, the program that one should be an individual and realize oneself. But this formula of being as unique as possible, different from others, dressing differently and so on, amounts to copying a trivial and banal program, i.e. precisely not being an individual. In the 19th century, there was still a discussion about this under religious auspices, which pointed out that individuality was given by God and given with the soul, and all the euphoria about individuality of the secular philosophers, that one had to be an individual and make an effort to become one through education or whatever, was basically a collective mania. This discussion already showed how futile it is to become an individual via socialization if one presupposes that socialization runs via the transmission of patterns. If, on the other hand, one starts from autopoiesis, it becomes easier to understand that the structuring of one's consciousness, one's memory, and one's preferences is the result of an individual system history that has something to do, not least, with the cultural offer to actualize conformity or deviation. If it were only about transmission and everything else had to be described as a defect, it would not be possible to explain how individuality comes about, because then there would only be a variety of copies, depending on the range of cultural differentiation."
