        "text": "If one assumes autopoiesis, socialization would instead be self-socialization. One can only bring oneself into a form which meets certain requirements in social intercourse, fulfills certain preconditions or can also trigger certain reaction modes, for example of a negative kind. I believe that only in this way - and not via the transmission thesis - one can explain the enormous diversity of individuals. If one assumes that consciousness is a kind of blank slate, and disregards the fact that it has at most certain minimal biological pre-programming, be it Chomsky's innate language skills, be it biologically based instincts, consciousness is enormously capable of being shaped. If, in contrast, culture and its offerings are seen as relatively uniform, one must explain how the high degree of individuality we observe comes about."
